<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-162-806  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 162 806.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Software Engineering  April 1989 v15 n4p492(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Performance characterization of quorum-consensus algorithms forreplicated data. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ahamad, Mustaque; Ammar, Mostafa H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Availability of data in a distributed system is popularly enhancedby replication, necessitating the use of algorithms to maintainconsistency of the replicated data.andP;  A model and performancemeasures for a replicated data system that employs aquorum-consensus algorithm for consistency maintenance isdeveloped.andP;  Both the proportion of successfully completedtransactions in a system where transactions are aborted in theface of unavailable data, and the mean response time in systemswhere transactions hold for data availability are considered.andO;There is shown to be an optimal degree of replication beyond whichthere is performance degradation for some quorum assignments.andO;Other quorum assignments have no optimal degree of replication.andO;Optimal read and write quorums that maximize the proportion ofsuccessful transactions are derived.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AlgorithmsReplicated Data BasesResponse TimeOn-Line Transaction Processing.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   Degree of replication. (graph)Optimal read quorum for successfully completed transactions.andO;(table)Optimal read quorum for response time. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>